node.text: We’re in New Orleans this week for Mardi Gras, so we stopped by Bellegarde Bakery for a tour with owner and baker Graison Gill. At this site that opened last summer, Bellegarde mills their own flour, then turns out around 7,500 loaves of bread a week. The entire process is done by hand, from the milling to the mixing to the shaping. (Head baker Max Hobson folds the dough at intervals as it rises, which works the gluten but is more gentle than kneading.) They also make several types of pasta with their flours, heirloom grits ground on their granite mill, and a few assorted pastries to sell to walk-ins. @bellegardebakery

Staying in tonight? We’ve got you covered for delicious recipes for a romantic dinner in, fun pink and red cocktails, and breakfast-in-bed ideas for tomorrow. Head to the link in bio for more. Happy Valentine’s Day!

Meet Robert Nelson. This man might just be the most prolific Saveur home cook. He's made more than 4,000 of our recipes. 4,000! And get this—he rarely, and we mean RARELY, repeats a recipe. In fact, since picking up his first issue of Saveur in 2007, there's only about six that he revisits again and again. So what are they? Head to the link in our bio for more. (And swipe through for a sneak peak). #eattheworld #homecooking #saveurreaders

Test kitchen director @katcontrol just got back from a long weekend eating through central London. Stay tuned for more on our top picks from the city. Can’t wait? Check out “London Calling” in our highlights.  #eattheworld, #london

The 15th Annual Small Foods Party was held last night at the American Visionary Art Museum in Baltimore. A celebration of miniature nibbles of every kind, from Jello molds to campfire s’mores to chicken curry and rice, the event invites tiny-food enthusiasts of all ages to go big (small) or go home, to benefit Moveable Feast, a local organization that brings meals to the chronically ill. Costumes are optional but embraced, and the spirit of the night perfectly embodies the odd charm of “Charm City”. As one of the original founders of the party, graphic designer Kelley Bell, put it, “Baltimoreans go all out on this sort of thing. We have such a keen sense of the absurd.” Kuru Kuru Sushi-ko took home the Golden Toothpick for best miniaturization of a food. Tiny Tipsy Tea Party won the grand prize trophy for their tray of high tea goodies, including itty bitty crumpets and petit fours.

“In April 2005, I was a college senior contemplating an advanced degree in library science and book conservation, even though what I really loved was cooking and working part-time at a local cheese shop in Wellesley, Massachusetts (👋 @wasikscheeseshop!) Then, Saveur published a special issue devoted to artisanal American cheeses. Five months later, I enrolled in culinary school. Today, these nine cheesemakers, all covered in that issue, still thrill me.” —Kat Craddock (@katcontrol), Saveur’s present-day Test Kitchen Director. Head to the link in our bio for more on these memorable and delicious cheeses. 📸: @brianklutch

Yeah, they wishin’ and wishin’ and wishin’ and wishin’ … they made cakes like these. Join Joy the Baker for a hands-on class @chswineandfood where you’ll learn the art of cake decorating, including piping techniques and how to write (Drake lyrics, of course) on a cake. At the end of this master class, you’ll be decorating like a (cake) boss and have your own “Drake on Cake” to show off. Tickets available at link in bio.

Boozy and easy. That's the perfect way to describe this beauty of a dessert. Known as Lalla Rookh (not to be confused with the cocktail by the same name) this retro-chic dish is essentially a rum-laced sundae that dates back to at least the early 20th century. Served in a leggy glass (think: champagne coup or long-stemmed flutes), it's as elegant as it is fun. And it's easy to make! (The secret to success? Use the best rum and ice cream you can find.) Head to the link in our bio for @nomoremrnicepie’s breakdown and recipe. #eattheworld 📸: @katcontrol

Saag paneer is likely highlighted as a "frequently ordered" item at your local Indian restaurant. But how much do you know about this North Indian classic?  Head to the link in our bio to learn more about the dish's background from @cathyerway — and for the recipe to make it over the weekend. #eattheworld 📸: @hellomydumpling 🥣: @tyna.hoang

The holidays may be over, but now is the time to make turkey leg confit. By cooking the drumsticks fully submerged in fat, you're left with rich, succulent meat that will last all winter in the fridge. @chefmarksteuer showed us how to do it, and shared his pretzel-sausage stuffing as the optimal side dish. Head to the link in our bio for the recipes. #eattehworld 📸: @hellomydumpling 🥣: @tyna.hoang

Saveur reader @feedtheswimmers has the right idea with our spinach and ricotta "ravioli nudi"—a stripped-down ravioli that's also a great way to get some greens in. It's one of our best recipes of all time featured in our 25th Anniversary issue—head to the link in our bio to see how to make them yourself! #eattheworld

We’re so happy to see our readers and followers cooking through some of our favorite recipes for the holiday season! Keep cooking, keep shooting, and keep tagging for a chance to be featured on our page. #saveurreaders #eattheworld

Our 25th Anniversary issue is out now! We’re so excited to see it in the hands of our readers—like it is here with @mayakaimal, former Saveur staffer and founder of @mayakaimalfoods. Be sure to share your favorite recipes and stories with the tag #saveurreaders for a chance to be featured here on our Instagram! #eattheworld

There are few dishes that bring the holiday drama like classic lobster thermidor. Here, tender lobster and earthy mushrooms are swathed in a rich mustard-cream sauce and finished with a layer of broiled @gruyere_aop cheese. Head to the link in our bio for the recipe.

The best part about this pie is that is doesn't require a rolling pin to make the hazelnut-gingersnap crust. The next best part is the lime custard filling and cranberry curd-marscapone cream that tops it. Head to the link in our bio to learn how to get it right from resident pie expert @nomoremrnicepie, and the recipe to bring this cheery pie to your holiday table. #eattheworld

Leftover smoked trout hash calls for over-easy eggs the next day. Catch @notesfromacook's recipe in our 25th Anniversary Issue and at the link in our bio. #eattheworld 🍳: @katcontrol 📸: @dj_costantino

Chef @gregbaxtrom brought the funky bites (like this duo of duck) and @gooseisland brought the brews (like this fruit-forward Matilda) for a feast in the SAVEUR test kitchen celebrating all things fermentation. ➡️➡️➡️Swipe through to see more of our favorite dishes, drinks, and highlights from the evening. #eattheworld #saveursuppers 📸: @martsromero

Though it's named for Ukraine's capital city, chicken Kiev is probably not Ukrainian. And while the dish's origins are contested, what's undeniable is the appeal of a crisp exterior and luscious core of dill-spiked compound butter that oozes once its cut into. Head to the link in our bio for how to get it right, and for a deep dive into chicken Kiev's complicated history with @cathyerway. #eattheworld 📸: @hellomydumpling 🥣: @tyna.hoang

Sweet, salty, and crunchy, this pumpkin seed brittle makes an excellent garnish or a delicious snack—or a thoughtful homemade holiday gift. Head to the link in our bio for the recipe from chef @markusglocker of @batardny #eattheworld

Fluffy, eggy, buttery, coiled like a snail’s shell, and generously dusted with powdered sugar, mallorcas are named for their land of origin in Spain—but their story doesn't end there. These sweet, spiral breads made their way across breakfast cultures to Puerto Rico, where they're often split and stuffed with ham and cheese for the ultimate sweet-and-savory sandwich. Read more about their journey—and get the recipe!—through the link in our bio. #eattheworld 📸: @evakolenko 📝: @eatgordaeat

The countdown is on for one of our all-time favorite food and wine festivals: Charleston Wine + Food is back for its 15th year. With 130 events over five days, the 2020 festival is guaranteed  to be full of delicious bites, flavorful sips, and good times. Snag your tickets today!

Crisp, bubbly, and filled with sweetened ricotta, cannoli are the pride of many Sicilian bakers—including chef @angela_rito's grandfather, Santo. He started baking them at age 8 in a pastry shop on the island and continues to do so at their family bakery, Rito's, in Cleveland. Angie continues the tradition at her restaurant @donangienyc. Head to the link in our bio for the recipe—and Grandpa Santo's cannoli secrets. #eattheworld 📸: @evakolenko

In this week's The Way We Cook column, @cathyerway traces how beef noodle soup, or niu rou mian, became the national dish of modern Taiwan. While these days you'll find the noodle soup on almost every corner of Taipei, 60 years ago, it wasn't much of a thing. The dish is a rich blend of influences from mainland China and Taiwan, often made with tomatoes to buoy the deep, earthy broth of beef shank. Learn how to make the perfect bowl through the link in our bio. #eattheworld 📸: @hellomydumpling 🥣: @tyna.hoang

A sleepy city on the South China Sea ruled by the Portuguese until 1999, Macau has become a glitzy playground for China's ultra-wealthy. But in pockets between the casino resorts fueled by mainland money, traces of its culinary history remain. Follow @kevinthepang as he explores Macau's stew of cooking traditions—a hybrid of Portuguese and Chinese, with sprinklings of Indian, Malay, and East African. It's a cuisine that could come from no place else on Earth. Read more through the link in our bio. #eattheworld 📸: @dylanandjeni

Learn how to make lobster thermidor, the most special of all special-occasion dishes. Chunks of tender lobster are smothered in a mustard-cream sauce, placed back in the lobster shell, and broiled under a @gruyere_aop cheese crust for a show-stopping presentation. Grab the recipe through the link in our bio.
